Li  Liu is a first-year master student in Computational Social Science at the University of Chicago. He works as a research assistant for the data analytics division at the Harris School of Public Policy. Previously, he held teaching assistant position for MBA regression course at the Booth School of Business. He had short-term working experience at organizations in e-commerce, media, education, and sales. He is enthusiastic about building data-driven models to understand and analyze the marketing activities using machine learning, data mining, econometrics, causal inference. He has finished empirical projects with different types of data, including scanner records, macroeconomic indexes, social networks, geospatial locations, labor force survey, houses images, and review texts. He earned a B.S. in Mathematics and B.A. in Economics from Indiana University Bloomington from 2015 to 2018. 
